Bill Stewart +1-908-949-0705 (wcs@anchor.ho.att.com) wrote:
: In article <2gpbf5$qte@hymir.ifi.uio.no> thork@ifi.uio.no (Thor Oddleif Kristoffersen) writes:
:    Why hasn't there been made any serious attempts to extend DES?


: There *have* been a number of attempts to extend DES or its (published
: or reengineered) design principles to better algorithms.
: It turns out to be difficult to improve without major redesign,
: and there's still the lingering suspicion of NSA backdoors.
: Simple approaches often weaken it rather than strengthening it,
: and don't solve the problem of defeating differential cryptanalysis.
: Bruce Schneier's book on Applied Cryptography devotes a reasonably
: long section to discussing extensions of DES.
: Some of the things people have done are to double the effective
: blocksize, requiring about 4-5 calls of basic DES,
: and to play around with more rounds of S-box, etc.

: The alternative approach is to do major redesigns (e.g. IDEA, Khufu etc.)
: and try to use software-friendly operations instead of
: hardware-oriented bit-twiddling.
: --
